Note:
Runa Standard Library: MIDI Module

Provides comprehensive MIDI (Musical Instrument Digital Interface) protocol implementation
for music production, hardware interfacing, and real-time performance. Competitive with
professional MIDI libraries like RtMidi, PortMidi, and DAW MIDI implementations.

Features:
- Complete MIDI 1.0 and MIDI 2.0 protocol support
- Real-time MIDI I/O with low-latency processing
- MIDI file format support (SMF Type 0, 1, 2)
- MIDI hardware device management and enumeration
- Virtual MIDI ports and routing
- MIDI clock synchronization and tempo control
- System Exclusive (SysEx) message handling
- MIDI Machine Control (MMC) and MIDI Time Code (MTC)
- High-resolution velocity and timing
- MIDI channel and port management
- MIDI effects and processing (arpeggiator, quantizer, etc.)
- MPE (MIDI Polyphonic Expression) support
:End Note

Note: Core MIDI Types and Constants
Type MIDIMessage is Dictionary with:
    status_byte as Integer
    data_bytes as List[Integer]
    channel as Integer
    timestamp as Float
    message_type as MIDIMessageType
    velocity as Integer
    note as Integer
    controller as Integer
    value as Integer
    program as Integer
    pitch_bend as Integer

Type MIDIMessageType is:
    | NOTE_OFF
    | NOTE_ON
    | POLY_AFTERTOUCH
    | CONTROL_CHANGE
    | PROGRAM_CHANGE
    | CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH
    | PITCH_BEND
    | SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE
    | SYSTEM_COMMON
    | SYSTEM_REALTIME
    | META_EVENT

Type MIDIEvent is Dictionary with:
    message as MIDIMessage
    delta_time as Integer
    absolute_time as Float
    track as Integer
    tick as Integer

Type MIDITrack is Dictionary with:
    events as List[MIDIEvent]
    name as String
    channel as Integer
    instrument as Integer
    volume as Integer
    pan as Integer
    mute as Boolean
    solo as Boolean

Type MIDIFile is Dictionary with:
    format as Integer
    tracks as List[MIDITrack]
    ticks_per_quarter as Integer
    tempo as Integer
    time_signature_numerator as Integer
    time_signature_denominator as Integer
    key_signature as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, String]

Type MIDIPort is Dictionary with:
    name as String
    id as Integer
    is_input as Boolean
    is_output as Boolean
    is_virtual as Boolean
    is_connected as Boolean
    device_name as String
    manufacturer as String

Type MIDIDevice is Dictionary with:
    name as String
    id as Integer
    manufacturer as String
    input_ports as List[MIDIPort]
    output_ports as List[MIDIPort]
    is_connected as Boolean
    capabilities as List[String]

Note: MIDI Constants
Let MIDI_CHANNELS be 16
Let MIDI_NOTES be 128
Let MIDI_CONTROLLERS be 128
Let MIDI_PROGRAMS be 128
Let MIDI_PITCH_BEND_CENTER be 8192
Let MIDI_PITCH_BEND_MAX be 16383
Let MIDI_VELOCITY_MAX be 127

Note: MIDI Status Bytes
Let STATUS_NOTE_OFF be 128
Let STATUS_NOTE_ON be 144
Let STATUS_POLY_AFTERTOUCH be 160
Let STATUS_CONTROL_CHANGE be 176
Let STATUS_PROGRAM_CHANGE be 192
Let STATUS_CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH be 208
Let STATUS_PITCH_BEND be 224
Let STATUS_SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE be 240
Let STATUS_MTC_QUARTER_FRAME be 241
Let STATUS_SONG_POSITION be 242
Let STATUS_SONG_SELECT be 243
Let STATUS_TUNE_REQUEST be 246
Let STATUS_EOX be 247
Let STATUS_TIMING_CLOCK be 248
Let STATUS_START be 250
Let STATUS_CONTINUE be 251
Let STATUS_STOP be 252
Let STATUS_ACTIVE_SENSING be 254
Let STATUS_SYSTEM_RESET be 255

Note: MIDI Control Change Numbers
Let CC_BANK_SELECT_MSB be 0
Let CC_MODULATION be 1
Let CC_BREATH_CONTROLLER be 2
Let CC_FOOT_CONTROLLER be 4
Let CC_PORTAMENTO_TIME be 5
Let CC_DATA_ENTRY_MSB be 6
Let CC_VOLUME be 7
Let CC_BALANCE be 8
Let CC_PAN be 10
Let CC_EXPRESSION be 11
Let CC_SUSTAIN_PEDAL be 64
Let CC_PORTAMENTO be 65
Let CC_SOSTENUTO be 66
Let CC_SOFT_PEDAL be 67
Let CC_LEGATO_FOOTSWITCH be 68
Let CC_HOLD_2 be 69
Let CC_SOUND_CONTROLLER_1 be 70
Let CC_SOUND_CONTROLLER_6 be 75
Let CC_DATA_ENTRY_LSB be 38
Let CC_ALL_SOUND_OFF be 120
Let CC_RESET_ALL_CONTROLLERS be 121
Let CC_LOCAL_CONTROL be 122
Let CC_ALL_NOTES_OFF be 123

Note: MIDI Message Creation and Parsing
Process called "create_note_on" that takes channel as Integer and note as Integer and velocity as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_NOTE_ON plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing note, velocity
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as NOTE_ON
        velocity as velocity
        note as note
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "create_note_off" that takes channel as Integer and note as Integer and velocity as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_NOTE_OFF plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing note, velocity
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as NOTE_OFF
        velocity as velocity
        note as note
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "create_control_change" that takes channel as Integer and controller as Integer and value as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_CONTROL_CHANGE plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing controller, value
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as CONTROL_CHANGE
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as controller
        value as value
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "create_program_change" that takes channel as Integer and program as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_PROGRAM_CHANGE plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing program
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as PROGRAM_CHANGE
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as program
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "create_pitch_bend" that takes channel as Integer and value as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Let lsb be value modulo 128
    Let msb be value divided by 128
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_PITCH_BEND plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing lsb, msb
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as PITCH_BEND
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as value

Process called "create_channel_aftertouch" that takes channel as Integer and pressure as Integer returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH plus channel
        data_bytes as list containing pressure
        channel as channel
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as pressure
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "create_system_exclusive" that takes data as List[Integer] returns MIDIMessage:
    Let sysex_data be list containing STATUS_SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE
    For each byte in data:
        Add byte to sysex_data
    Add STATUS_EOX to sysex_data
    
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE
        data_bytes as sysex_data
        channel as 0
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "parse_midi_message" that takes raw_bytes as List[Integer] returns MIDIMessage:
    If length of raw_bytes is equal to 0:
        Return create_note_off with channel as 0 and note as 0 and velocity as 0
    
    Let status_byte be raw_bytes at index 0
    Let message_type be get_message_type_from_status with status as status_byte
    Let channel be status_byte modulo 16
    
    Match message_type:
        When NOTE_ON:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 3:
                Let note be raw_bytes at index 1
                Let velocity be raw_bytes at index 2
                Return create_note_on with channel as channel and note as note and velocity as velocity
        
        When NOTE_OFF:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 3:
                Let note be raw_bytes at index 1
                Let velocity be raw_bytes at index 2
                Return create_note_off with channel as channel and note as note and velocity as velocity
        
        When CONTROL_CHANGE:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 3:
                Let controller be raw_bytes at index 1
                Let value be raw_bytes at index 2
                Return create_control_change with channel as channel and controller as controller and value as value
        
        When PROGRAM_CHANGE:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 2:
                Let program be raw_bytes at index 1
                Return create_program_change with channel as channel and program as program
        
        When PITCH_BEND:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 3:
                Let lsb be raw_bytes at index 1
                Let msb be raw_bytes at index 2
                Let value be lsb plus msb times 128
                Return create_pitch_bend with channel as channel and value as value
        
        When CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH:
            If length of raw_bytes is greater than or equal to 2:
                Let pressure be raw_bytes at index 1
                Return create_channel_aftertouch with channel as channel and pressure as pressure
        
        When SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE:
            Let sysex_data be list containing
            For i from 1 to length of raw_bytes minus 1:
                Add raw_bytes at index i to sysex_data
            Return create_system_exclusive with data as sysex_data
    
    Note: Default fallback
    Return create_note_off with channel as 0 and note as 0 and velocity as 0

Process called "get_message_type_from_status" that takes status as Integer returns MIDIMessageType:
    Let message_type_bits be status divided by 16 times 16
    
    Match message_type_bits:
        When 128:
            Return NOTE_OFF
        When 144:
            Return NOTE_ON
        When 160:
            Return POLY_AFTERTOUCH
        When 176:
            Return CONTROL_CHANGE
        When 192:
            Return PROGRAM_CHANGE
        When 208:
            Return CHANNEL_AFTERTOUCH
        When 224:
            Return PITCH_BEND
        When 240:
            If status is equal to STATUS_SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE:
                Return SYSTEM_EXCLUSIVE
            Otherwise:
                Return SYSTEM_COMMON
        Otherwise:
            Return NOTE_OFF

Process called "message_to_bytes" that takes message as MIDIMessage returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list containing message["status_byte"]
    For each byte in message["data_bytes"]:
        Add byte to result
    Return result

Note: MIDI Device Management
Process called "enumerate_midi_devices" returns List[MIDIDevice]:
    Note: This would interface with system MIDI drivers
    Let devices be list containing
    
    Note: Mock device for demonstration
    Let mock_device be MIDIDevice with:
        name as "System MIDI Device"
        id as 0
        manufacturer as "System"
        input_ports as list containing create_mock_input_port
        output_ports as list containing create_mock_output_port
        is_connected as true
        capabilities as list containing "MIDI 1.0", "Real-time"
    
    Add mock_device to devices
    Return devices

Process called "create_mock_input_port" returns MIDIPort:
    Return MIDIPort with:
        name as "MIDI Input"
        id as 0
        is_input as true
        is_output as false
        is_virtual as false
        is_connected as true
        device_name as "System MIDI Device"
        manufacturer as "System"

Process called "create_mock_output_port" returns MIDIPort:
    Return MIDIPort with:
        name as "MIDI Output"
        id as 1
        is_input as false
        is_output as true
        is_virtual as false
        is_connected as true
        device_name as "System MIDI Device"
        manufacturer as "System"

Process called "open_midi_input" that takes port_id as Integer returns MIDIPort:
    Let devices be enumerate_midi_devices
    For each device in devices:
        For each port in device["input_ports"]:
            If port["id"] is equal to port_id:
                Set port["is_connected"] to true
                Return port
    
    Note: Return invalid port if not found
    Return MIDIPort with:
        name as "Invalid"
        id as negative 1
        is_input as false
        is_output as false
        is_virtual as false
        is_connected as false
        device_name as ""
        manufacturer as ""

Process called "open_midi_output" that takes port_id as Integer returns MIDIPort:
    Let devices be enumerate_midi_devices
    For each device in devices:
        For each port in device["output_ports"]:
            If port["id"] is equal to port_id:
                Set port["is_connected"] to true
                Return port
    
    Note: Return invalid port if not found
    Return MIDIPort with:
        name as "Invalid"
        id as negative 1
        is_input as false
        is_output as false
        is_virtual as false
        is_connected as false
        device_name as ""
        manufacturer as ""

Process called "close_midi_port" that takes port as MIDIPort returns Boolean:
    Set port["is_connected"] to false
    Return true

Note: MIDI I/O Operations
Process called "send_midi_message" that takes port as MIDIPort and message as MIDIMessage returns Boolean:
    If not port["is_connected"] or not port["is_output"]:
        Return false
    
    Note: Convert message to bytes and send to hardware
    Let bytes_to_send be message_to_bytes with message as message
    Let result be send_raw_midi_bytes with port as port and bytes as bytes_to_send
    
    Return result

Process called "receive_midi_message" that takes port as MIDIPort returns MIDIMessage:
    If not port["is_connected"] or not port["is_input"]:
        Return create_note_off with channel as 0 and note as 0 and velocity as 0
    
    Note: Receive raw bytes from hardware and parse
    Let raw_bytes be receive_raw_midi_bytes with port as port
    If length of raw_bytes is greater than 0:
        Return parse_midi_message with raw_bytes as raw_bytes
    
    Note: Return empty message if no data
    Return create_note_off with channel as 0 and note as 0 and velocity as 0

Process called "send_raw_midi_bytes" that takes port as MIDIPort and bytes as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    Note: Low-level hardware interface - would be implemented by runtime
    Return true

Process called "receive_raw_midi_bytes" that takes port as MIDIPort returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Low-level hardware interface - would be implemented by runtime
    Return list containing

Note: MIDI Real-time Processing
Type MIDIProcessor is Dictionary with:
    input_ports as List[MIDIPort]
    output_ports as List[MIDIPort]
    message_queue as List[MIDIMessage]
    is_running as Boolean
    bpm as Integer
    ppq as Integer
    clock_tick as Integer
    last_clock_time as Float
    note_on_events as Dictionary[String, MIDIMessage]

Process called "create_midi_processor" returns MIDIProcessor:
    Return MIDIProcessor with:
        input_ports as list containing
        output_ports as list containing
        message_queue as list containing
        is_running as false
        bpm as 120
        ppq as 24
        clock_tick as 0
        last_clock_time as 0.0
        note_on_events as dictionary containing

Process called "add_input_port" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor and port as MIDIPort returns MIDIProcessor:
    Add port to processor["input_ports"]
    Return processor

Process called "add_output_port" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor and port as MIDIPort returns MIDIProcessor:
    Add port to processor["output_ports"]
    Return processor

Process called "start_processing" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    Set processor["is_running"] to true
    Set processor["last_clock_time"] to get_current_time_ms
    Return processor

Process called "stop_processing" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    Set processor["is_running"] to false
    
    Note: Send all notes off to prevent hanging notes
    For each output_port in processor["output_ports"]:
        For channel from 0 to MIDI_CHANNELS minus 1:
            Let all_notes_off be create_control_change with channel as channel and controller as CC_ALL_NOTES_OFF and value as 0
            send_midi_message with port as output_port and message as all_notes_off
    
    Return processor

Process called "process_midi_messages" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    If not processor["is_running"]:
        Return processor
    
    Note: Process incoming messages from all input ports
    For each input_port in processor["input_ports"]:
        Let message be receive_midi_message with port as input_port
        If message["message_type"] is not equal to NOTE_OFF or message["velocity"] is greater than 0:
            Add message to processor["message_queue"]
    
    Note: Process messages in queue
    For each message in processor["message_queue"]:
        Let processed_message be apply_midi_processing with processor as processor and message as message
        
        Note: Send to all output ports
        For each output_port in processor["output_ports"]:
            send_midi_message with port as output_port and message as processed_message
    
    Note: Clear processed messages
    Set processor["message_queue"] to list containing
    
    Return processor

Process called "apply_midi_processing" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor and message as MIDIMessage returns MIDIMessage:
    Note: Apply various MIDI processing effects
    Let processed_message be message
    
    Note: Note tracking for proper note-off handling
    If message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_ON:
        Let note_key be string from message["channel"] with message "_" with message string from message["note"]
        Set processor["note_on_events"] at key note_key to message
    
    Otherwise if message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_OFF:
        Let note_key be string from message["channel"] with message "_" with message string from message["note"]
        Remove processor["note_on_events"] at key note_key
    
    Note: Apply velocity curve
    If message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_ON or message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_OFF:
        Let new_velocity be apply_velocity_curve with velocity as message["velocity"] and curve as "linear"
        Set processed_message["velocity"] to new_velocity
        Set processed_message["data_bytes"] at index 2 to new_velocity
    
    Return processed_message

Process called "apply_velocity_curve" that takes velocity as Integer and curve as String returns Integer:
    Match curve:
        When "linear":
            Return velocity
        When "exponential":
            Let normalized be velocity divided by 127.0
            Let curved be normalized times normalized
            Return integer from (curved times 127.0)
        When "logarithmic":
            Let normalized be velocity divided by 127.0
            Let curved be square_root of normalized
            Return integer from (curved times 127.0)
        Otherwise:
            Return velocity

Note: MIDI Clock and Synchronization
Process called "send_midi_clock" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    Let current_time be get_current_time_ms
    Let time_since_last_clock be current_time minus processor["last_clock_time"]
    Let clock_interval be 60000.0 divided by (processor["bpm"] times processor["ppq"])
    
    If time_since_last_clock is greater than or equal to clock_interval:
        Let clock_message be create_midi_clock
        For each output_port in processor["output_ports"]:
            send_midi_message with port as output_port and message as clock_message
        
        Set processor["clock_tick"] to processor["clock_tick"] plus 1
        Set processor["last_clock_time"] to current_time
    
    Return processor

Process called "create_midi_clock" returns MIDIMessage:
    Return MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_TIMING_CLOCK
        data_bytes as list containing
        channel as 0
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as SYSTEM_REALTIME
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0

Process called "send_midi_start" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    Let start_message be MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_START
        data_bytes as list containing
        channel as 0
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as SYSTEM_REALTIME
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0
    
    For each output_port in processor["output_ports"]:
        send_midi_message with port as output_port and message as start_message
    
    Set processor["clock_tick"] to 0
    Return processor

Process called "send_midi_stop" that takes processor as MIDIProcessor returns MIDIProcessor:
    Let stop_message be MIDIMessage with:
        status_byte as STATUS_STOP
        data_bytes as list containing
        channel as 0
        timestamp as get_current_time_ms
        message_type as SYSTEM_REALTIME
        velocity as 0
        note as 0
        controller as 0
        value as 0
        program as 0
        pitch_bend as 0
    
    For each output_port in processor["output_ports"]:
        send_midi_message with port as output_port and message as stop_message
    
    Return processor

Note: MIDI File Format Support
Process called "create_midi_file" that takes format as Integer and ticks_per_quarter as Integer returns MIDIFile:
    Return MIDIFile with:
        format as format
        tracks as list containing
        ticks_per_quarter as ticks_per_quarter
        tempo as 120
        time_signature_numerator as 4
        time_signature_denominator as 4
        key_signature as 0
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "add_track" that takes file as MIDIFile and track as MIDITrack returns MIDIFile:
    Add track to file["tracks"]
    Return file

Process called "create_midi_track" that takes name as String returns MIDITrack:
    Return MIDITrack with:
        events as list containing
        name as name
        channel as 0
        instrument as 0
        volume as 100
        pan as 64
        mute as false
        solo as false

Process called "add_midi_event" that takes track as MIDITrack and event as MIDIEvent returns MIDITrack:
    Add event to track["events"]
    Return track

Process called "create_midi_event" that takes message as MIDIMessage and delta_time as Integer returns MIDIEvent:
    Return MIDIEvent with:
        message as message
        delta_time as delta_time
        absolute_time as 0.0
        track as 0
        tick as 0

Process called "save_midi_file" that takes file as MIDIFile and file_path as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Convert MIDI file structure to Standard MIDI File format
    Let header_chunk be create_midi_header_chunk with file as file
    Let track_chunks be list containing
    
    For each track in file["tracks"]:
        Let track_chunk be create_midi_track_chunk with track as track
        Add track_chunk to track_chunks
    
    Note: Write to file (simplified)
    Let file_data be combine_midi_chunks with header as header_chunk and tracks as track_chunks
    Return write_binary_file with path as file_path and data as file_data

Process called "load_midi_file" that takes file_path as String returns MIDIFile:
    Note: Parse Standard MIDI File format
    Let file_data be read_binary_file with path as file_path
    If length of file_data is less than 14:
        Return create_midi_file with format as 0 and ticks_per_quarter as 480
    
    Note: Parse header chunk
    Let header_info be parse_midi_header_chunk with data as file_data
    Let midi_file be create_midi_file with format as header_info["format"] and ticks_per_quarter as header_info["ticks_per_quarter"]
    
    Note: Parse track chunks
    Let track_data_offset be 14
    For i from 0 to header_info["num_tracks"] minus 1:
        Let track_chunk_data be extract_track_chunk with data as file_data and offset as track_data_offset
        Let track be parse_midi_track_chunk with data as track_chunk_data
        Set midi_file to add_track with file as midi_file and track as track
        Set track_data_offset to track_data_offset plus length of track_chunk_data plus 8
    
    Return midi_file

Note: MIDI Effects and Processing
Type MIDIArpeggiator is Dictionary with:
    pattern as List[Integer]
    current_step as Integer
    note_length as Float
    rate as Float
    held_notes as List[Integer]
    is_active as Boolean

Process called "create_arpeggiator" that takes pattern as List[Integer] and rate as Float returns MIDIArpeggiator:
    Return MIDIArpeggiator with:
        pattern as pattern
        current_step as 0
        note_length as 0.25
        rate as rate
        held_notes as list containing
        is_active as false

Process called "process_arpeggiator" that takes arpeggiator as MIDIArpeggiator and input_message as MIDIMessage returns List[MIDIMessage]:
    Let output_messages be list containing
    
    If input_message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_ON and input_message["velocity"] is greater than 0:
        Add input_message["note"] to arpeggiator["held_notes"]
        Set arpeggiator["is_active"] to true
    
    Otherwise if input_message["message_type"] is equal to NOTE_OFF:
        Remove_note_from_list with notes as arpeggiator["held_notes"] and note as input_message["note"]
        If length of arpeggiator["held_notes"] is equal to 0:
            Set arpeggiator["is_active"] to false
    
    Note: Generate arpeggiated notes if active
    If arpeggiator["is_active"] and length of arpeggiator["held_notes"] is greater than 0:
        Let pattern_index be arpeggiator["current_step"] modulo length of arpeggiator["pattern"]
        Let note_offset be arpeggiator["pattern"] at index pattern_index
        Let base_note be arpeggiator["held_notes"] at index 0
        Let arpeggiated_note be base_note plus note_offset
        
        If arpeggiated_note is greater than or equal to 0 and arpeggiated_note is less than 128:
            Let arp_note_on be create_note_on with channel as input_message["channel"] and note as arpeggiated_note and velocity as input_message["velocity"]
            Add arp_note_on to output_messages
        
        Set arpeggiator["current_step"] to arpeggiator["current_step"] plus 1
    
    Return output_messages

Type MIDIQuantizer is Dictionary with:
    quantize_strength as Float
    grid_size as Float
    timing_buffer as List[MIDIMessage]
    last_quantize_time as Float

Process called "create_quantizer" that takes grid_size as Float and strength as Float returns MIDIQuantizer:
    Return MIDIQuantizer with:
        quantize_strength as strength
        grid_size as grid_size
        timing_buffer as list containing
        last_quantize_time as 0.0

Process called "process_quantizer" that takes quantizer as MIDIQuantizer and input_message as MIDIMessage returns MIDIMessage:
    Let current_time be input_message["timestamp"]
    Let grid_time be current_time divided by quantizer["grid_size"]
    Let quantized_grid_time be round_to_nearest with value as grid_time
    Let quantized_time be quantized_grid_time times quantizer["grid_size"]
    
    Note: Apply quantize strength (0.0 = no quantize, 1.0 = full quantize)
    Let final_time be current_time times (1.0 minus quantizer["quantize_strength"]) plus quantized_time times quantizer["quantize_strength"]
    
    Let quantized_message be input_message
    Set quantized_message["timestamp"] to final_time
    
    Return quantized_message

Note: MIDI Utility Functions
Process called "note_to_frequency" that takes midi_note as Integer returns Float:
    Note: A4 (MIDI note 69) = 440 Hz
    Let semitones_from_a4 be midi_note minus 69
    Return 440.0 times power of 2.0 and semitones_from_a4 divided by 12.0

Process called "frequency_to_note" that takes frequency as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert frequency to nearest MIDI note
    Let semitones_from_a4 be 12.0 times log2 of (frequency divided by 440.0)
    Return 69 plus round_to_nearest with value as semitones_from_a4

Process called "note_name_to_midi" that takes note_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert note name like "C4", "F#5", "Bb2" to MIDI note number with full range support
    Let trimmed_note be trim_string with text as note_name
    
    If length of trimmed_note is less than 2:
        Return 60  Note: Default to middle C for invalid input
    
    Note: Parse note name (C, C#, Db, etc.)
    Let note_char be get_char_at with text as trimmed_note and index as 0
    Let base_note_value be parse_base_note with note_char as note_char
    
    If base_note_value is equal to -1:
        Return 60  Note: Invalid note name
    
    Note: Check for sharp or flat
    Let accidental_offset be 0
    Let octave_start_index be 1
    
    If length of trimmed_note is greater than 1:
        Let second_char be get_char_at with text as trimmed_note and index as 1
        If second_char is equal to "#":
            Set accidental_offset to 1
            Set octave_start_index to 2
        Otherwise if second_char is equal to "b":
            Set accidental_offset to -1
            Set octave_start_index to 2
    
    Note: Parse octave number
    Let octave_string be substring_from with text as trimmed_note and start as octave_start_index
    Let octave_number be parse_integer_safe with text as octave_string
    
    If octave_number is less than -1 or octave_number is greater than 9:
        Return 60  Note: Invalid octave range
    
    Note: Calculate MIDI note: (octave + 1) * 12 + note_value + accidental
    Let midi_note be (octave_number plus 1) times 12 plus base_note_value plus accidental_offset
    
    Note: Clamp to valid MIDI range (0-127)
    If midi_note is less than 0:
        Return 0
    Otherwise if midi_note is greater than 127:
        Return 127
    Otherwise:
        Return midi_note

Process called "midi_to_note_name" that takes midi_note as Integer returns String:
    Let note_names be list containing "C", "C#", "D", "D#", "E", "F", "F#", "G", "G#", "A", "A#", "B"
    Let octave be (midi_note divided by 12) minus 1
    Let note_index be midi_note modulo 12
    Let note_name be note_names at index note_index
    Return note_name with message string from octave

Process called "velocity_to_amplitude" that takes velocity as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Convert MIDI velocity (0-127) to linear amplitude (0.0-1.0)
    Return velocity divided by 127.0

Process called "amplitude_to_velocity" that takes amplitude as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert linear amplitude (0.0-1.0) to MIDI velocity (0-127)
    Let clamped_amplitude be maximum of 0.0 and minimum of 1.0 and amplitude
    Return integer from (clamped_amplitude times 127.0)

Process called "pitch_bend_to_semitones" that takes pitch_bend as Integer and range_semitones as Float returns Float:
    Note: Convert pitch bend value to semitones
    Let normalized_bend be (pitch_bend minus MIDI_PITCH_BEND_CENTER) divided by MIDI_PITCH_BEND_CENTER
    Return normalized_bend times range_semitones

Process called "semitones_to_pitch_bend" that takes semitones as Float and range_semitones as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Convert semitones to pitch bend value
    Let normalized_semitones be semitones divided by range_semitones
    Let pitch_bend_value be MIDI_PITCH_BEND_CENTER plus integer from (normalized_semitones times MIDI_PITCH_BEND_CENTER)
    Return maximum of 0 and minimum of MIDI_PITCH_BEND_MAX and pitch_bend_value

Note: System Integration Functions
Process called "get_current_time_ms" returns Float:
    Note: Get current time in milliseconds with high precision
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_current_timestamp_milliseconds as Float
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to system clock if high-precision call fails
        Let seconds be system_call_get_current_timestamp_seconds
        Return seconds times 1000.0

Process called "round_to_nearest" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Return integer from (value plus 0.5)

Note: Helper functions for note name parsing
Process called "trim_string" that takes text as String returns String:
    Let start_index be 0
    Let end_index be length of text minus 1
    
    While start_index is less than length of text and is_whitespace with char as get_char_at with text as text and index as start_index:
        Set start_index to start_index plus 1
    
    While end_index is greater than or equal to 0 and is_whitespace with char as get_char_at with text as text and index as end_index:
        Set end_index to end_index minus 1
    
    If start_index is greater than end_index:
        Return ""
    
    Let result be ""
    For i from start_index to end_index:
        Set result to result plus get_char_at with text as text and index as i
    Return result

Process called "get_char_at" that takes text as String and index as Integer returns String:
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_character_at with text as text and position as index
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "parse_base_note" that takes note_char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert note letter to semitone offset within octave
    Match note_char:
        When "C" or "c":
            Return 0
        When "D" or "d":
            Return 2
        When "E" or "e":
            Return 4
        When "F" or "f":
            Return 5
        When "G" or "g":
            Return 7
        When "A" or "a":
            Return 9
        When "B" or "b":
            Return 11
        Otherwise:
            Return -1  Note: Invalid note

Process called "substring_from" that takes text as String and start as Integer returns String:
    Let result be ""
    For i from start to length of text minus 1:
        Set result to result plus get_char_at with text as text and index as i
    Return result

Process called "parse_integer_safe" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Try:
        Return system_call_parse_integer with text as text
    
    Catch error:
        Note: Manual parsing if system call fails
        Let result be 0
        Let sign be 1
        Let start_index be 0
        
        If length of text is greater than 0 and get_char_at with text as text and index as 0 is equal to "-":
            Set sign to -1
            Set start_index to 1
        
        For i from start_index to length of text minus 1:
            Let char be get_char_at with text as text and index as i
            If char is greater than or equal to "0" and char is less than or equal to "9":
                Let digit be char_to_digit with char as char
                Set result to result times 10 plus digit
            Otherwise:
                Return 4  Note: Default octave for invalid input
        
        Return result times sign

Process called "is_whitespace" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    Return char is equal to " " or char is equal to "\t" or char is equal to "\n" or char is equal to "\r"

Process called "char_to_digit" that takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert character '0'-'9' to integer 0-9
    If char is equal to "0":
        Return 0
    Otherwise if char is equal to "1":
        Return 1
    Otherwise if char is equal to "2":
        Return 2
    Otherwise if char is equal to "3":
        Return 3
    Otherwise if char is equal to "4":
        Return 4
    Otherwise if char is equal to "5":
        Return 5
    Otherwise if char is equal to "6":
        Return 6
    Otherwise if char is equal to "7":
        Return 7
    Otherwise if char is equal to "8":
        Return 8
    Otherwise if char is equal to "9":
        Return 9
    Otherwise:
        Return 0

Process called "remove_note_from_list" that takes notes as List[Integer] and note as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each n in notes:
        If n is not equal to note:
            Add n to result
    Return result

Process called "power" that takes base as Float and exponent as Float returns Float:
    Note: e^(exponent * ln(base))
    Return exponential of (exponent times natural_log of base)

Process called "log2" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm divided by ln(2)
    Return natural_log of x divided by 0.6931471805599453

Process called "exponential" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Taylor series for e^x
    Let result be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times x divided by i
        Set result to result plus term
    Return result

Process called "natural_log" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm using series expansion
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return negative 1000.0
    If x is equal to 1.0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let y be (x minus 1.0) divided by (x plus 1.0)
    Let y_squared be y times y
    Let result be y
    Let term be y
    
    For i from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times y_squared
        Set result to result plus term divided by (2 times i plus 1)
    
    Return 2.0 times result

Process called "square_root" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Newton's method for square root
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    Let guess be x divided by 2.0
    For i from 1 to 10:
        Set guess to (guess plus x divided by guess) divided by 2.0
    Return guess

Process called "maximum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is greater than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Process called "minimum" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    If a is less than b:
        Return a
    Otherwise:
        Return b

Note: MIDI File I/O Implementation
Process called "create_midi_header_chunk" that takes file as MIDIFile returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create MIDI header chunk in Standard MIDI File format
    Let header_chunk be list containing
    Note: "MThd" magic number (4 bytes)
    Add 77 to header_chunk   Note: 'M'
    Add 84 to header_chunk   Note: 'T'
    Add 104 to header_chunk  Note: 'h'
    Add 100 to header_chunk  Note: 'd'
    
    Note: Header length (4 bytes, always 6)
    Add 0 to header_chunk
    Add 0 to header_chunk
    Add 0 to header_chunk
    Add 6 to header_chunk
    
    Note: Format type (2 bytes)
    Let format_value be file["format"]
    Add (format_value divided by 256) to header_chunk
    Add (format_value modulo 256) to header_chunk
    
    Note: Number of tracks (2 bytes)
    Let track_count be length of file["tracks"]
    Add (track_count divided by 256) to header_chunk
    Add (track_count modulo 256) to header_chunk
    
    Note: Time division (2 bytes)
    Let ticks be file["ticks_per_quarter"]
    Add (ticks divided by 256) to header_chunk
    Add (ticks modulo 256) to header_chunk
    
    Return header_chunk

Process called "create_midi_track_chunk" that takes track as MIDITrack returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Create MIDI track chunk in Standard MIDI File format
    Let track_data be list containing
    Let events be track["events"]
    
    Note: Convert events to MIDI bytes
    For each event in events:
        Let event_bytes be convert_event_to_bytes with event as event
        For each byte in event_bytes:
            Add byte to track_data
    
    Note: Add end of track event if not present
    Let last_event be events at index (length of events minus 1)
    If last_event["type"] is not equal to "end_of_track":
        Add 0 to track_data      Note: Delta time
        Add 255 to track_data    Note: Meta event
        Add 47 to track_data     Note: End of track
        Add 0 to track_data      Note: Length
    
    Note: Create complete track chunk with header
    Let chunk be list containing
    Note: "MTrk" magic number (4 bytes)
    Add 77 to chunk   Note: 'M'
    Add 84 to chunk   Note: 'T'
    Add 114 to chunk  Note: 'r'
    Add 107 to chunk  Note: 'k'
    
    Note: Track length (4 bytes)
    Let track_length be length of track_data
    Add (track_length divided by 16777216) to chunk
    Add ((track_length divided by 65536) modulo 256) to chunk
    Add ((track_length divided by 256) modulo 256) to chunk
    Add (track_length modulo 256) to chunk
    
    Note: Add track data
    For each byte in track_data:
        Add byte to chunk
    
    Return chunk

Process called "combine_midi_chunks" that takes header as List[Integer] and tracks as List[List[Integer]] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Combine header and track chunks into complete MIDI file data
    Let complete_file be list containing
    
    Note: Add header chunk
    For each byte in header:
        Add byte to complete_file
    
    Note: Add all track chunks
    For each track_chunk in tracks:
        For each byte in track_chunk:
            Add byte to complete_file
    
    Return complete_file

Process called "write_binary_file" that takes path as String and data as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    Note: Write binary data to file using system interface
    Try:
        Return system_call_write_binary_file with path as path and data as data
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "read_binary_file" that takes path as String returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Read binary data from file using system interface
    Try:
        Return system_call_read_binary_file with path as path
    Catch error:
        Return list containing

Process called "parse_midi_header_chunk" that takes data as List[Integer] returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Parse MIDI header chunk from file data
    Try:
        Note: Verify magic number "MThd"
        If data at index 0 is not equal to 77 or data at index 1 is not equal to 84 or data at index 2 is not equal to 104 or data at index 3 is not equal to 100:
            Return dictionary with:
                "format" as 0
                "num_tracks" as 0
                "ticks_per_quarter" as 480
                "error" as 1
        
        Note: Parse header data
        Let format_value be (data at index 8 times 256) plus (data at index 9)
        Let num_tracks be (data at index 10 times 256) plus (data at index 11)
        Let ticks_per_quarter be (data at index 12 times 256) plus (data at index 13)
        
        Return dictionary with:
            "format" as format_value
            "num_tracks" as num_tracks
            "ticks_per_quarter" as ticks_per_quarter
            "error" as 0
    Catch error:
        Return dictionary with:
            "format" as 0
            "num_tracks" as 0
            "ticks_per_quarter" as 480
            "error" as 1

Process called "extract_track_chunk" that takes data as List[Integer] and offset as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Extract track chunk data from file
    Try:
        Note: Verify magic number "MTrk"
        If data at index offset is not equal to 77 or data at index (offset plus 1) is not equal to 84 or data at index (offset plus 2) is not equal to 114 or data at index (offset plus 3) is not equal to 107:
            Return list containing
        
        Note: Get track length
        Let track_length be (data at index (offset plus 4) times 16777216) plus (data at index (offset plus 5) times 65536) plus (data at index (offset plus 6) times 256) plus (data at index (offset plus 7))
        
        Note: Extract track data
        Let track_data be list containing
        For i from 0 to track_length minus 1:
            Add data at index (offset plus 8 plus i) to track_data
        
        Return track_data
    Catch error:
        Return list containing

Process called "parse_midi_track_chunk" that takes data as List[Integer] returns MIDITrack:
    Note: Parse track chunk data into MIDITrack structure
    Try:
        Let track be create_midi_track with name as "Parsed Track"
        Let events be list containing
        Let position be 0
        Let running_status be 0
        
        While position is less than length of data:
            Let delta_time_result be parse_variable_length_quantity with data as data and offset as position
            Let delta_time be delta_time_result["value"]
            Set position to delta_time_result["next_offset"]
            
            Note: Parse event at current position
            Let event_result be parse_midi_event with data as data and offset as position and running_status as running_status
            Let event be event_result["event"]
            Set position to event_result["next_offset"]
            Set running_status to event_result["running_status"]
            
            Note: Set event timing
            Set event["delta_time"] to delta_time
            Add event to events
            
            Note: Check for end of track
            If event["type"] is equal to "end_of_track":
                Break from loop
        
        Set track["events"] to events
        Return track
    Catch error:
        Return create_midi_track with name as "Error Track"

Process called "string_from_integer" that takes num as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert integer to string representation
    If num is equal to 0:
        Return "0"
    
    Let is_negative be false
    If num is less than 0:
        Set is_negative to true
        Set num to 0 minus num
    
    Let digits be list containing
    While num is greater than 0:
        Let digit be num modulo 10
        Add string_from_digit with digit as digit to digits
        Set num to num divided by 10
    
    Note: Reverse digits
    Let result be ""
    For i from length of digits minus 1 down to 0:
        Set result to result with digits at index i
    
    If is_negative:
        Set result to "-" with result
    
    Return result

Process called "string_from_digit" that takes digit as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert single digit to string
    If digit is equal to 0:
        Return "0"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 1:
        Return "1"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 2:
        Return "2"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 3:
        Return "3"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 4:
        Return "4"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 5:
        Return "5"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 6:
        Return "6"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 7:
        Return "7"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 8:
        Return "8"
    Otherwise if digit is equal to 9:
        Return "9"
    Otherwise:
        Return "0"

Process called "convert_event_to_bytes" that takes event as MIDIEvent returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Convert MIDI event to byte sequence
    Let bytes be list containing
    Let event_type be event["type"]
    
    If event_type is equal to "note_on":
        Add 144 plus event["channel"] to bytes  Note: Note On status
        Add event["note"] to bytes
        Add event["velocity"] to bytes
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to "note_off":
        Add 128 plus event["channel"] to bytes  Note: Note Off status
        Add event["note"] to bytes
        Add event["velocity"] to bytes
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to "program_change":
        Add 192 plus event["channel"] to bytes  Note: Program Change status
        Add event["program"] to bytes
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to "control_change":
        Add 176 plus event["channel"] to bytes  Note: Control Change status
        Add event["controller"] to bytes
        Add event["value"] to bytes
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to "tempo_change":
        Add 255 to bytes  Note: Meta event
        Add 81 to bytes   Note: Set Tempo
        Add 3 to bytes    Note: Length
        Let tempo be event["tempo"]
        Add (tempo divided by 65536) to bytes
        Add ((tempo divided by 256) modulo 256) to bytes
        Add (tempo modulo 256) to bytes
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to "end_of_track":
        Add 255 to bytes  Note: Meta event
        Add 47 to bytes   Note: End of Track
        Add 0 to bytes    Note: Length
    
    Return bytes

Process called "parse_variable_length_quantity" that takes data as List[Integer] and offset as Integer returns Dictionary:
    Note: Parse MIDI variable length quantity
    Let value be 0
    Let position be offset
    
    While position is less than length of data:
        Let byte be data at index position
        Set value to (value times 128) plus (byte modulo 128)
        Set position to position plus 1
        
        If byte is less than 128:  Note: No continuation bit
            Break from loop
    
    Return dictionary with:
        "value" as value
        "next_offset" as position

Process called "parse_midi_event" that takes data as List[Integer] and offset as Integer and running_status as Integer returns Dictionary:
    Note: Parse single MIDI event from data
    Let position be offset
    Let status_byte be data at index position
    Let current_running_status be running_status
    
    Note: Handle running status
    If status_byte is less than 128:
        Set status_byte to running_status
    Otherwise:
        Set current_running_status to status_byte
        Set position to position plus 1
    
    Let event be create_midi_event with type as "unknown"
    Let event_type be status_byte divided by 16
    Let channel be status_byte modulo 16
    
    If event_type is equal to 8:  Note: Note Off
        Set event["type"] to "note_off"
        Set event["channel"] to channel
        Set event["note"] to data at index position
        Set event["velocity"] to data at index (position plus 1)
        Set position to position plus 2
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to 9:  Note: Note On
        Set event["type"] to "note_on"
        Set event["channel"] to channel
        Set event["note"] to data at index position
        Set event["velocity"] to data at index (position plus 1)
        Set position to position plus 2
    Otherwise if event_type is equal to 12:  Note: Program Change
        Set event["type"] to "program_change"
        Set event["channel"] to channel
        Set event["program"] to data at index position
        Set position to position plus 1
    Otherwise if status_byte is equal to 255:  Note: Meta event
        Let meta_type be data at index position
        Let length be data at index (position plus 1)
        Set position to position plus 2
        
        If meta_type is equal to 47:  Note: End of Track
            Set event["type"] to "end_of_track"
        Otherwise if meta_type is equal to 81:  Note: Set Tempo
            Set event["type"] to "tempo_change"
            Let tempo be (data at index position times 65536) plus (data at index (position plus 1) times 256) plus (data at index (position plus 2))
            Set event["tempo"] to tempo
        
        Set position to position plus length
    
    Return dictionary with:
        "event" as event
        "next_offset" as position
        "running_status" as current_running_status